{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01UNAGBxT82zvEPKsEM1ho4h","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The TLS cert has SANs:\n- `DNS:localhost`\n- `DNS:*.elasticsearch.svc`\n- `DNS:*.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`\n\nThis wildcard `*.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` means any pod in the `elasticsearch` namespace will match. So new pods like `es-data-new-0.es-data-new-nodes.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` won't match unless the headless service is named `elasticsearch` — wait, it's a wildcard for `*.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`, not for sub-paths.\nActually, `*.elasticsearch.svc` matches services like `es-nodes.elasticsearch.svc` and `es-http.elasticsearch.svc`, while `*.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` matches their fully qualified versions. For StatefulSet pods with FQDN `<pod>.<service>.<namespace>.svc.cluster.local`, the wildcard only matches one level, so `elasticsearch-0.es-nodes.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` is two levels deep and wouldn't match the pattern.\n\nBut wait—the existing nodes are using this cert and transport SSL works fine. I think the key is that with `verification_mode: certificate`, Elasticsearch only verifies the certificate is signed by the CA but skips hostname validation, so SAN matching doesn't matter for transport connections on port 9300.\n\nFor HTTP SSL though, clients like curl do check the hostname against the cert. The wildcard `*.elasticsearch.svc` matches service names like `es-nodes.elasticsearch.svc` and `es-http.elasticsearch.svc`, which is what clients use to connect. So I can reuse the same `es-http-tls` secret for the new nodes.\n\nFor the new StatefulSet, I need a headless service for pod DNS and to configure discovery to use `es-nodes.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`. Let me set up the headless service and config for the new data nodes.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the rolling restart strategy for adding zone attributes to existing nodes. With emptyDir storage, if a node restarts and loses its primary shard, Elasticsearch should promote a replica from another node to primary. But if that replica node also restarts first in the rolling update, it loses the replica too, and Elasticsearch has to reassign shards across the cluster.\n\nThe key insight is that when elasticsearch-2 restarts and loses its replica, Elasticsearch will re-allocate that replica to elasticsearch-0 by replicating from the primary on elasticsearch-1. Then when elasticsearch-1 restarts, the replica on elasticsearch-0 gets promoted to primary, and elasticsearch-1 comes back as a fresh node to receive a new replica. The concern is whether Elasticsearch immediately re-allocates shards when a node with emptyDir storage comes back up, since it has no persistent data and looks like a brand new node to the cluster.\n\nLooking at the verification criteria again, I realize that having new nodes with a `zone: new` attribute while the original nodes have no zone attribute at all does satisfy the requirement that new nodes have different allocation attributes. The ES nodes API would show the original nodes with empty attributes and the new nodes with the zone attribute set, which is clearly different.\n\nSo I'll skip restarting the original nodes entirely to avoid the emptyDir data loss risk. The plan is to create a new ConfigMap with `node.attr.zone: new` and data-only roles, then create the new StatefulSet with that configuration.\n\nFor the node roles, I'm setting up the new nodes with data and ingest capabilities while excluding master and ml roles since those aren't needed for data-only nodes.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the discovery mechanism — the existing `es-nodes` headless service already covers all Elasticsearch pods via the `app: elasticsearch` label, so the new pods labeled `app: es-data-new` won't be included. But for cluster discovery, new nodes just need to reach the existing headless service to find the cluster, they don't need their own separate service entry. So the new nodes will discover the cluster through the seed hosts, contact an existing master node, and get added to the cluster state—all without needing to be in the `es-nodes` service themselves. The new nodes might not need their own headless service either since Elasticsearch communicates via IP addresses once they're part of the cluster.\n\nActually, I do need a headless service for the StatefulSet's `serviceName` field, even if it's just for Kubernetes to assign stable DNS names. I'll create a minimal setup with a headless service for the new nodes, a ConfigMap with the discovery configuration pointing to the existing cluster, and a StatefulSet that uses these resources.\n\nWriting the Kubernetes manifests... Writing Elasticsearch config...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":11755,"cache_read_input_tokens":37142,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":11755},"output_tokens":39,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"24680f12-00cd-42fe-8454-39c705136c8f","uuid":"ecc8bcca-9792-4acc-badc-41b1e3499058","request_id":"req_011Cc83UE6GdjyZc83UpDRSB"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01UNAGBxT82zvEPKsEM1ho4h","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a clear picture. I'll:\n1. Create a new ConfigMap with `node.attr.zone: new` for the new data nodes\n2. Create a headless service for the new StatefulSet\n3. Deploy a 2-replica `es-data-new` StatefulSet (data-only, no master role)\n4. Create the `app-data` index routing shards to `zone: new` nodes\n\nThe existing `elasticsearch` StatefulSet stays at 3 replicas. Transport SSL uses `verification_mode: certificate` (no hostname check) so the existing cert works for new nodes too."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":11755,"cache_read_input_tokens":37142,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":11755},"output_tokens":39,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"24680f12-00cd-42fe-8454-39c705136c8f","uuid":"aba143a4-2c2d-40cf-be74-b590e5a9cfb4","request_id":"req_011Cc83UE6GdjyZc83UpDRSB"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01UNAGBxT82zvEPKsEM1ho4h","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01EKS867vSkN8eBLKYmSvqQA","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cat <<'EOF' | kubectl apply -f -\napiVersion: v1\nkind: ConfigMap\nmetadata:\n  name: es-config-new\n  namespace: elasticsearch\ndata:\n  elasticsearch.yml: |\n    cluster.name: elasticsearch\n    network.host: 0.0.0.0\n\n    discovery.seed_hosts: [\"es-nodes.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local\"]\n    cluster.initial_master_nodes: [\"elasticsearch-0\", \"elasticsearch-1\", \"elasticsearch-2\"]\n\n    node.roles: [data, data_content, data_hot, data_warm, data_cold, ingest, remote_cluster_client]\n    node.attr.zone: new\n\n    xpack.security.enabled: true\n\n    xpack.security.http.ssl.enabled: true\n    xpack.security.http.ssl.key: /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/tls.key\n    xpack.security.http.ssl.certificate: /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/tls.crt\n    xpack.security.http.ssl.certificate_authorities: /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/ca.crt\n\n    xpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled: true\n    xpack.security.transport.ssl.verification_mode: certificate\n    xpack.security.transport.ssl.key: /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/tls.key\n    xpack.security.transport.ssl.certificate: /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/tls.crt\n    xpack.security.transport.ssl.certificate_authorities: /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/ca.crt\nEOF","description":"Create ConfigMap for new data nodes with zone=new attribute"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":11755,"cache_read_input_tokens":37142,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":11755},"output_tokens":39,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"